    {
      "id": "-mmMGtJ-COd2QeVrkTcXt",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 177.69878603412928,
      "y": -1283.3049700534298,
      "width": 1752.4000244140625,
      "height": 3800,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b3i",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 774660132,
      "version": 15062,
      "versionNonce": 1320337828,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1768797130376,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "GitHub CI/CD\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n   1. Commit Pushed to Github repository should trigger an automatic build and deployment to regions via your own CI/CD server\n   2. Users can see the status of their workflow.\n   3. Users can see the logs generated for their workflow.\n   4. Users can retry or cancel their workflow (along with automated retry)\n\nScale - \n   1. 10M Repos and 10 commits per day per repo ~= 1000 commits/sec\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. Workflow should be able to run in a sandboxed environment, without harming the CI/CD Server\n   2. Viewing status and logs of their workflow can be eventual and should be highly available.\n   3. Status should be automatically reflected on the client's browser (SSE) within 500ms\n   4. Logs should also be automatically reflected on the client's browser within 500ms.\n   5. System should be able to handle a burst traffic of 1K commits/sec to 10K commits/sec.\n\nOut of scope - \n   1. Code Freeze would have lots of piled workflows. We should select the latest one.\n\n\nAPI Routes - \n\n1. POST /commit/\n\n{\n     repoId:\n     author:\n     Type: Source\n     timestamp:\n     ParentCommitId\n     CommitMessage\n     CommitHash:\n     CommitPayload: \n}\n\n2. GET /workflow/<workflowId>\n\n{\n     TopCommitId:\n     TopCommitMessage:\n     TopCommitAuthor:\n     RepoId:\n     Status: {Started|Completed|Failed|Retried}\n     CreationTimestamp\n     LastModifiedTimestamp:\n     Jobs: Array[Job]\n}\n\n3. GET /workflow/<workflowId>?logsEnabled\n\n{\n     // Logs getting streamed\n     // timestamp\n}\n\n4. POST /workflow/ \n\n{\n      workflowId:\n      Action: Retry/Cancel\n      timestamp\n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Push a commit to the GitHub server\n      a. The server validates if the parent commit id is equal to the last commit id (Optimistic checking)\n          and if it matches, the server creates a new manifest file which is the copy of the previous manifest\n          file.\n      b. Post the payload received from the local is a snapshot of the modified files only.\n      c. So, in the new manifest file, it replaces the hash of those files to the new commit hash and persist in the\n          blob storage\n      d. Manifest --> {filename (M) --> CommitHash, fileName (Non-M) --> oldCommitHash}\n      e. Blob storage has folders named with hash and it can fetch the code directly from there.\n      f. When somebody does git pull, it obtains the last commitID from the local and do a diff of commits and \n          provide the top commit ID with its manifest URL which has the hash of every file and it only downloads\n          the code from those commit hashes.\n\n2. Notification sent from GitHub Server\n    a. When the commit is pushed, the git hub server fires a notification to my serverless Lambda. \n    b. I have a load balancer to my server less lambda because if this bridge breaks, I might have to re-trigger the \n        failures from Github server. The Github server is a fire-and-forget mechanism. This will have ops pain if not maintained\n        correctly. With 1K to 10K commits/sec, Lambda will get over-whelmed. So, a load balancer will route the request\n        evenly to maintain the health of X instances of Lambda\n    c. The Lambda is very light-weight and it's only responsibility is to push the notification to the SQS.\n    d. SQS persists the data in its disk for some days, so my notification is not lost.\n\n\n3. CI/CD Server integration\n      a. The CI/CD Server will consumes the notification from the SQS which will contain the recently pushed commit ID\n          and the manifest URL and create the workflow with status 'STARTED'.\n      b. The CI/CD Server then request the configuration files from the Github repo (.YAML) file to construct the workflow order as Graph\n           with Build/Test -->  Deploy To RegionA --> Deploy To RegionB.\n      c. Then the server creates JOBS with status as NOTSTARTED and dependentOnJobId and queueId. Post that, it queues them in in Build queues and update the \n          WORKFLOW table with status as IN_PROGRESS\n      d. A Build/Test Worker Server will poll the workflow from the Build queue, update the JOBS table and start a VM/Container process --> proceed with VM \n            1. Pull the code from GitHubServer\n            2. Build\n            3. Execute Unit/Integration Tests\n            4. Create artifacts such as shared/static libraries and executable bins\n     e. Upload the artifacts to S3 and then update the workflow DB with 'COMPLETED' as status in the JOBS table and S3 artifacts URL.\n     f. Post that, it creates a notification to Deployment (Region-specific) queues. Region-Specific Deployment Worker polls from the queue and look at the resources\n          that they need to deploy to and trigger deployment and update the Workflow DB with 'IN_PROGRESS' as status in the JOBS table\n     g. Now if the workflow says the next step is to deploy to IAD, we will have region-specific queues and Region-specific deployment worker for every region.\n\n4. User wants to see the status of their workflow\n     a. User makes a GET request to the workflow server which fetches the status of the workflow and displays it to the user. However, the user needs to query\n        the workflow server to see if there is a change in status. As per the requirement, we need to show the change in status in real time (< 500ms)\n     b. In order to achieve this, we will introduce a Pub/Sub mechanism. If 1 user is interested to view the workflow, the workflow server takes the responsibility\n         of creating the topic as workflowID and subscribing to it and updating in the workflow DB. Now, if 10 users join different instances of the server, \n         those instances will check if the workflowID has a topicID and if it is present in the DB, those instances will subscribe to it,\n     c. Whenever there is a change in the workflow DB, the lambda will consume the message from DynamoDB streams (CDC event) and will publish to the topicID. \n     d. The workflow servers will maintain an in-memory mapping of topicID to SSE connection and if they receive an update, it will send it to the user's browser.\n\n5. User cancels a workflow\n     a. The user can send a POST request to a Workflow server to cancel the workflow. The server immediately updates the workflow DB with status 'USER_ABORTED'.\n         and queries all the jobs with status as IN-PROGRESS and workflowId = workflowID and and update their status with \"USER_ABORTED\".\n     b. This will trigger a CDC event and the status will be updated to the browser. However, the lambda will take an additional responsibility of \n          intimating the active worker instance Id (Maybe build or deployment worker) to gracefully exit the current stage of the workflow.\n     c. There are cases that if a deployment has started and a request to abort has been made, the deployment worker needs to rollback to previous changes\n         and this is the graceful exit i am taking about. Post that the deployment worker will update the workflow DB with ABORTED status in JOBS and WORKFLOW tables.\n\n5. User retries a workflow.\n    a. User sends a POST request to the Workflow server to retry the workflow and server fetches all the jobs which belongs to the workflow and status as FAILED. \n        It resets the retryCount, sets the status as 'NOT-STARTED' in JOBS table and 'IN-PROGRESS' in WORKFLOW table and pushes the same request to the \n        queue which it fetched from the JOB table.\n    b. IT will trigger 2 CDC events - one to show the RETRY in progress and then will switch to STARTED when a worker polls from the queue and update the DB.\n\n6. User sees logs of their workflow\n    a. Every Job will generate logs and every worker should take the responsibility to flush the logs to the database. Since Logs are Append only, we can use a WAL database\n        but the volume of the logs will be too high and soon the database will hit the bottleneck.\n    b. So, we batch the logs in a event stream to be consumed by some serverless Lambda and then persist them in the database. Similar to WORKFLOW DB, we will have\n        CDC event which will be consumed by Lambda and then will publish to the Pub/Sub so that the users connected to the workflow server can view the logs in near real time.\n\n\nLet's talk about scaling - \n      a. All Lambdas are stateless so they can scale dynamically.\n      b. The Notification Queue from Git Hub Server needs ordered commits per repoId. We can shard the queue via repoID as Ordered SQS can support 3K messages/sec in a message group (repo)\n      c. The CI/CD and WORKFLOW server is stateless and can scale dynamically depending upon the Notification Queue Depth.\n      d. Workflow DB which is a relational DB have a lot of write paths and for 1 commit, it can be invoked more than 10 times. Hence, we can have the DB sharded by repoId too and if a shard is \n          getting hot, we can spin up replicas so that reads can be diverted to them while the primary shard takes the write heat.\n      e. All the other job queues can be shared based on repoId again to maintain ordering where commit B gets deployed first and then commit A which will override the latest commit.\n      f. Worker Servers are stateless so they can scale dynamically.\n     g. EventStreams should also maintain ordering and hence can be shared by repoId.\n     h. PubSub can be sharded by workflowId as not every workflow of a repo would require near real-time views.\n     i. WAL Database can be sharded by repoId.\n\n\n\n    ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "GitHub CI/CD\n\nFunctional Requirements - \n   1. Commit Pushed to Github repository should trigger an automatic build and deployment to regions via your own CI/CD server\n   2. Users can see the status of their workflow.\n   3. Users can see the logs generated for their workflow.\n   4. Users can retry or cancel their workflow (along with automated retry)\n\nScale - \n   1. 10M Repos and 10 commits per day per repo ~= 1000 commits/sec\n\nNon-Functional Requirements - \n   1. Workflow should be able to run in a sandboxed environment, without harming the CI/CD Server\n   2. Viewing status and logs of their workflow can be eventual and should be highly available.\n   3. Status should be automatically reflected on the client's browser (SSE) within 500ms\n   4. Logs should also be automatically reflected on the client's browser within 500ms.\n   5. System should be able to handle a burst traffic of 1K commits/sec to 10K commits/sec.\n\nOut of scope - \n   1. Code Freeze would have lots of piled workflows. We should select the latest one.\n\n\nAPI Routes - \n\n1. POST /commit/\n\n{\n     repoId:\n     author:\n     Type: Source\n     timestamp:\n     ParentCommitId\n     CommitMessage\n     CommitHash:\n     CommitPayload: \n}\n\n2. GET /workflow/<workflowId>\n\n{\n     TopCommitId:\n     TopCommitMessage:\n     TopCommitAuthor:\n     RepoId:\n     Status: {Started|Completed|Failed|Retried}\n     CreationTimestamp\n     LastModifiedTimestamp:\n     Jobs: Array[Job]\n}\n\n3. GET /workflow/<workflowId>?logsEnabled\n\n{\n     // Logs getting streamed\n     // timestamp\n}\n\n4. POST /workflow/ \n\n{\n      workflowId:\n      Action: Retry/Cancel\n      timestamp\n}\n\nHigh Level Design \n\n1. Push a commit to the GitHub server\n      a. The server validates if the parent commit id is equal to the last commit id (Optimistic checking)\n          and if it matches, the server creates a new manifest file which is the copy of the previous manifest\n          file.\n      b. Post the payload received from the local is a snapshot of the modified files only.\n      c. So, in the new manifest file, it replaces the hash of those files to the new commit hash and persist in the\n          blob storage\n      d. Manifest --> {filename (M) --> CommitHash, fileName (Non-M) --> oldCommitHash}\n      e. Blob storage has folders named with hash and it can fetch the code directly from there.\n      f. When somebody does git pull, it obtains the last commitID from the local and do a diff of commits and \n          provide the top commit ID with its manifest URL which has the hash of every file and it only downloads\n          the code from those commit hashes.\n\n2. Notification sent from GitHub Server\n    a. When the commit is pushed, the git hub server fires a notification to my serverless Lambda. \n    b. I have a load balancer to my server less lambda because if this bridge breaks, I might have to re-trigger the \n        failures from Github server. The Github server is a fire-and-forget mechanism. This will have ops pain if not maintained\n        correctly. With 1K to 10K commits/sec, Lambda will get over-whelmed. So, a load balancer will route the request\n        evenly to maintain the health of X instances of Lambda\n    c. The Lambda is very light-weight and it's only responsibility is to push the notification to the SQS.\n    d. SQS persists the data in its disk for some days, so my notification is not lost.\n\n\n3. CI/CD Server integration\n      a. The CI/CD Server will consumes the notification from the SQS which will contain the recently pushed commit ID\n          and the manifest URL and create the workflow with status 'STARTED'.\n      b. The CI/CD Server then request the configuration files from the Github repo (.YAML) file to construct the workflow order as Graph\n           with Build/Test -->  Deploy To RegionA --> Deploy To RegionB.\n      c. Then the server creates JOBS with status as NOTSTARTED and dependentOnJobId and queueId. Post that, it queues them in in Build queues and update the \n          WORKFLOW table with status as IN_PROGRESS\n      d. A Build/Test Worker Server will poll the workflow from the Build queue, update the JOBS table and start a VM/Container process --> proceed with VM \n            1. Pull the code from GitHubServer\n            2. Build\n            3. Execute Unit/Integration Tests\n            4. Create artifacts such as shared/static libraries and executable bins\n     e. Upload the artifacts to S3 and then update the workflow DB with 'COMPLETED' as status in the JOBS table and S3 artifacts URL.\n     f. Post that, it creates a notification to Deployment (Region-specific) queues. Region-Specific Deployment Worker polls from the queue and look at the resources\n          that they need to deploy to and trigger deployment and update the Workflow DB with 'IN_PROGRESS' as status in the JOBS table\n     g. Now if the workflow says the next step is to deploy to IAD, we will have region-specific queues and Region-specific deployment worker for every region.\n\n4. User wants to see the status of their workflow\n     a. User makes a GET request to the workflow server which fetches the status of the workflow and displays it to the user. However, the user needs to query\n        the workflow server to see if there is a change in status. As per the requirement, we need to show the change in status in real time (< 500ms)\n     b. In order to achieve this, we will introduce a Pub/Sub mechanism. If 1 user is interested to view the workflow, the workflow server takes the responsibility\n         of creating the topic as workflowID and subscribing to it and updating in the workflow DB. Now, if 10 users join different instances of the server, \n         those instances will check if the workflowID has a topicID and if it is present in the DB, those instances will subscribe to it,\n     c. Whenever there is a change in the workflow DB, the lambda will consume the message from DynamoDB streams (CDC event) and will publish to the topicID. \n     d. The workflow servers will maintain an in-memory mapping of topicID to SSE connection and if they receive an update, it will send it to the user's browser.\n\n5. User cancels a workflow\n     a. The user can send a POST request to a Workflow server to cancel the workflow. The server immediately updates the workflow DB with status 'USER_ABORTED'.\n         and queries all the jobs with status as IN-PROGRESS and workflowId = workflowID and and update their status with \"USER_ABORTED\".\n     b. This will trigger a CDC event and the status will be updated to the browser. However, the lambda will take an additional responsibility of \n          intimating the active worker instance Id (Maybe build or deployment worker) to gracefully exit the current stage of the workflow.\n     c. There are cases that if a deployment has started and a request to abort has been made, the deployment worker needs to rollback to previous changes\n         and this is the graceful exit i am taking about. Post that the deployment worker will update the workflow DB with ABORTED status in JOBS and WORKFLOW tables.\n\n5. User retries a workflow.\n    a. User sends a POST request to the Workflow server to retry the workflow and server fetches all the jobs which belongs to the workflow and status as FAILED. \n        It resets the retryCount, sets the status as 'NOT-STARTED' in JOBS table and 'IN-PROGRESS' in WORKFLOW table and pushes the same request to the \n        queue which it fetched from the JOB table.\n    b. IT will trigger 2 CDC events - one to show the RETRY in progress and then will switch to STARTED when a worker polls from the queue and update the DB.\n\n6. User sees logs of their workflow\n    a. Every Job will generate logs and every worker should take the responsibility to flush the logs to the database. Since Logs are Append only, we can use a WAL database\n        but the volume of the logs will be too high and soon the database will hit the bottleneck.\n    b. So, we batch the logs in a event stream to be consumed by some serverless Lambda and then persist them in the database. Similar to WORKFLOW DB, we will have\n        CDC event which will be consumed by Lambda and then will publish to the Pub/Sub so that the users connected to the workflow server can view the logs in near real time.\n\n\nLet's talk about scaling - \n      a. All Lambdas are stateless so they can scale dynamically.\n      b. The Notification Queue from Git Hub Server needs ordered commits per repoId. We can shard the queue via repoID as Ordered SQS can support 3K messages/sec in a message group (repo)\n      c. The CI/CD and WORKFLOW server is stateless and can scale dynamically depending upon the Notification Queue Depth.\n      d. Workflow DB which is a relational DB have a lot of write paths and for 1 commit, it can be invoked more than 10 times. Hence, we can have the DB sharded by repoId too and if a shard is \n          getting hot, we can spin up replicas so that reads can be diverted to them while the primary shard takes the write heat.\n      e. All the other job queues can be shared based on repoId again to maintain ordering where commit B gets deployed first and then commit A which will override the latest commit.\n      f. Worker Servers are stateless so they can scale dynamically.\n     g. EventStreams should also maintain ordering and hence can be shared by repoId.\n     h. PubSub can be sharded by workflowId as not every workflow of a repo would require near real-time views.\n     i. WAL Database can be sharded by repoId.\n\n\n\n    ",
